On Mon, 03 Feb 2003 12:37:06 -0500, &quot;Francois Beausoleil&quot;
&lt;fbeausoleil@...&gt; said:
&gt; Hello everyone,
&gt; 
&gt; I have a project on SourceForge.net which I started a while ago.  I named
&gt; it &quot;Extensible Java Unit-testing Framework&quot; (ejuf for short).  This
&gt; project is using a reusable assertion mechanism.  I am using the Jakarta
&gt; &quot;Byte Code Engineering Library&quot; to implement assertion interfaces into
&gt; testable objects.
&gt; 
&gt; For example, let&#39;s say you want to use XML assertions and DB assertions
&gt; in the same test case, you would do something like this:
&gt; public abstract MyXmlAndDbCase implements Testable, XmlAssertions,
&gt; DbAssertions, EqualityAssertions {
&gt;    public void testSomething() {
&gt;       // Uses an object that implements XmlAssertions that was previously
&gt;       configured
&gt;       assertXmlEquals(...);
&gt; 
&gt;       // Uses an object that implements DbAssertions that was previously
&gt;       configured
&gt;       assertDbEquals(...); // I don&#39;t know actual method names, but this
&gt;       is for illustration purposes
&gt; 
&gt;       // Uses an object that implements EqualityAssertions that was
&gt;       previously configured
&gt;       assertEquals(...);
&gt;    }
&gt; }
&gt; 
&gt; This way of doing things provides me with a completely vendor and
&gt; extension neutral way of doing things.  Additionnaly, I have other things
&gt; in there to help testing.
&gt; 
&gt; For more information, you may access the project&#39;s CVS repository.  I
&gt; have successfully used EJUF in two or three projects of mine.  Obviously,
&gt; EJUF is able to test itself :)
&gt; 
&gt; I consider the code ready for prime-time, except that there is almost no
&gt; documentation.  WARNING:  There is a failure in the tests right now
&gt; because that is where I left off.  I had started doing XmlConfiguration
&gt; stuff, but that is not finished.  But the rest is actually very usable.
&gt; 
&gt; If you want to take a look at the project and report back, I would be
&gt; more than happy to help and respond to comments, although such
&gt; discussions might be more appropriate on EJUF&#39;s mailing lists...
&gt; 
&gt; Thank you,
&gt; Francois Beausoleil
&gt; http://sourceforge.net/projects/ejuf/
&gt; 
&gt; On Mon, 3 Feb 2003 10:49:57 +0900 (JST), &quot;Curt Sampson&quot;
&gt; &lt;yahoo_sucks@...&gt; said:
&gt; &gt; On Sun, 2 Feb 2003, Scott Stirling wrote:
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; &gt; Why not just extend TestCase with specialized, re-usable, TestCase types?
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; I do already. In fact, many times: we have a base test case for our
&gt; &gt; company which adds various handy generic stuff (such as byte-array
&gt; &gt; comparisons), inheriting from that often a test case for a project
&gt; &gt; adding some project specific-stuff, inheriting from that in certain
&gt; &gt; packages a package-specific test case adding stuff for the servlet or
&gt; &gt; DB testing or whatever, and so on.
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; Unfortunately, it&#39;s not very modular; if someone supplies me with
&gt; &gt; a ExtendedTestCaseOne and another person supplies me with an
&gt; &gt; ExtendedTestCaseTwo, each of which has certain features I want, I can&#39;t
&gt; &gt; inherit from both. And again, the test cases tend to collect more and
&gt; &gt; more code, becoming this massive objects with massive functionality (and
&gt; &gt; correspondingly massive tests)....
&gt; &gt; 
&gt; &gt; My primary feeling here (whether supportable or not) is that a TestCase
&gt; &gt; could be a lot smaller and simpler if we could move most of the
&gt; &gt; assertion checking and assertion message generation code out of it.
&gt; &gt; As well it would also give us the ability to easily add different
&gt; &gt; ways of asserting where and when we need them, without having to use
&gt; &gt; inheritance to bring in new implemenations of something. (I&#39;m a big fan
&gt; &gt; of type inheritance; I&#39;m rather dubious about the use of inheritance for
&gt; &gt; implemenation purposes only.)
